PREPARING ALL THE DATA

In order to start we download the .csv files from https://opendata-ajuntament.barcelona.cat/data/en/dataset/contaminants-estacions-mesura-qualitat-aire. When importing the files to RStudio, we have to set the working directory to where the files are located.

library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)

setwd("~/DATA ANALYSIS/AIR QUALITY/FINAL PROJETC")

jan <- read.csv("2022_01_Gener_qualitat_aire_BCN.csv")

We merge all the datasets together to have a common 2022 dataset. We use the union function as we want all the observations in the dataset, one after the other.

jan_feb <- union(jan,feb)

m3 <-union(jan_feb,mar)

m4 <- union(m3,apr)

m5 <- union(m4,may)

m6 <- union(m5,jun)

m7 <- union(m6,jul)

m9 <- union(m8,sep)

m10 <- union(m9,oct)

m11 <- union(m10,nov)

air2022 <- union(m11,dec)

alltrees <- union(trees, st_trees)

We delete the datasets created before, keeping the air2022 and alltrees datasets.

rm(jan,feb,jan_feb,mar,apr,may,jun,jul,aug,sep,oct,nov,dec,m3,m4,m5,m6,m7,m8,m9,m10,m11)
rm(trees, st_trees)

We delete all NA values.

cair <- na.omit(air2022)

We convert the H variables and their values into observations so we can analyze and plot the information easier.

pivair <- cair %>% 
  pivot_longer(
    cols = starts_with("H"),
    names_to = "Hours",
    names_prefix = "H",
    values_to = "Pollution_lvl",
    values_drop_na = TRUE
  )
pivair2 <- pivair[,-c(10:33)]
pivair <- pivair2
rm(pivair2)

We create a function so when R reads the number of the district, it will tell the name of the district. Then, we mutate the dataset for the variable districte to follow the delimitated function (using names of district instead of numbers).

est_f <- function(x){
  cut(
    x,
    breaks = c(-Inf, 4, 42, 43, 44, 50, 54, 57, 58, Inf),
    labels = c("San Marti", "Sants-Montjuic", "Eixample", "Gracia", "Ciutat Vella", "Horta-Guinardo", "Les Corts", "Sarria-Sant Gervasi", "NA")
  )
}
air2 <- mutate(pivair, DISTRICTE = est_f(ESTACIO))

We now count the number of trees per district.

gtrees <- group_by(alltrees, nom_districte)
strees <- summarise(gtrees, Arboles = n())

strees2 <- strees

ANALYZING THE DATA

Analyzing trees in each district

ggplot(strees) +
  geom_col(mapping = aes(x = DISTRICTE, y = ARBRES))+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title = "TREES PER DISTRICT")+
  xlab("DISTRICT")+
  ylab("TREES")

In this graph we can see the number of trees in each district. The neighborhood of Sant Marti is the one that has the highest number of trees with almost 40000, and Gràcia the one with less, with an approximate amount of 10000

Analayzing the presence of each contaminant per district

Following, we analize how the level of each contaminant in each district and we delete the contaminants that aren’t useful.

gcont2 <- group_by(air2, CODI_CONTAMINANT, DISTRICTE)
scont2 <- summarise(gcont2, count = n())
scont3 <- filter(scont2, CODI_CONTAMINANT != 901, CODI_CONTAMINANT != 996, CODI_CONTAMINANT != 997,
                 CODI_CONTAMINANT != 998, CODI_CONTAMINANT != 999, CODI_CONTAMINANT != 106, CODI_CONTAMINANT != 107,
                 CODI_CONTAMINANT != 108, CODI_CONTAMINANT != 109, CODI_CONTAMINANT != 110, CODI_CONTAMINANT != 112,
                 CODI_CONTAMINANT != 114, CODI_CONTAMINANT != 101)
ggplot(scont3)+
  geom_col(mapping = aes(x = as.character(CODI_CONTAMINANT), y = count, fill = DISTRICTE), position = "dodge")+
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(6500,8250))+
  labs(title = "CONTAMINANT CODE OBSERVATIONS PER DISTRICT")+
  xlab("CONTAMINANT CODE")+
  ylab("OBSERVATIONS")

In this graph we can see the relationship between the repetition of times the contaminants have been given a value and each contaminant for each neighborhood. We can easily see that not all neighborhoods have contaminants. There is no neighborhood that stands out because of their high level of pollution

ggplot(scont3)+
  geom_tile(mapping = aes(x = as.character(CODI_CONTAMINANT), y = DISTRICTE, fill = count))+
  labs(title = "CONTAMINANT CODE OBSERVATIONS PER DISTRICT", fill = "OBSERVATIONS")+
  xlab("CONTAMINANT CODE")

We used this graph to represent the same information as above but with a different style. We are evaluating the contaminant code per each district and the amount of repetitions of each. We can see that the light blue areas are the different districts that have a high amount of a specific contaminant, and the opposite happens with the dark blue areas.

Analyzing each contaminant separately by district

SO2

SO2 <- filter(air2, CODI_CONTAMINANT == 1)
gSO2 <- group_by(SO2, DISTRICTE)
sSO2 <- summarise(gSO2, Polucion = mean(Pollution_lvl))
SO2tree <- left_join(sSO2, strees, by = "DISTRICTE")
ggplot(SO2tree)+
  geom_col(mapping = aes(x = Polucion, y = DISTRICTE, fill = ARBRES))+
  labs(title = "SO2 POLLUTION PER DISTRICT")+
  xlab("POLLUTION")

In this graph we can see the relationship between the districts that have the contaminant SO2 and the pollution levels of this one, taking into consideration the number of trees in each area. There is an existence of a relationship between the number of trees and the SO2 pollution levels, meaning that if there are more trees in the neighborhood there is less pollution. Take for example the district of Gràcia, which doesn’t have many trees and therefore the pollution levels of this contaminant are high. In contrast, in Eixample, the opposite thing happens, lots of trees and less pollution.

CONCLUSION

Overall, from all the contaminants, we can barely see any relationship between the pollution levels and the number of trees.This is probably because we are analyzing the number of trees per area and not their density of trees per area. So, the districts that have a higher number of trees are probably bigger and so pollute more.

Analyzing the data in a timely manner

Contaminacio mensual

#CONTAMINACION MENSUAL
poljan <- group_by(air2, MES)
poljan2 <- summarise(poljan, Polucion = mean(Pollution_lvl))

ggplot(poljan2)+
  geom_col(mapping = aes(x = MES, y = Polucion))+
  labs(title = "MONTHLY POLLUTION LEVEL DURING 2022")+
  ylab("POLLUTION")+
  xlab("MONTH")

In the first months of the year, the pollution levels are higher. The pollution levels of the first two months of the year are higher than the rest, although there is a peak in July. After that increase, the pollution levels decrease again. Overall, all the months represent more or less the same amount of pollution.

Contaminacio diaria

#CONTAMINACION DIARIA
poldia <- group_by(air2, MES, DIA)
poldia2 <- summarise(poldia, Polucion = mean(Pollution_lvl))
poldia2$count <- seq_len(nrow(poldia2))
ggplot(poldia2)+
  geom_col(mapping = aes(x = count, y = Polucion))+
  labs(title = "DAILY POLLUTION LEVEL DURING 2022")+
  xlab("DAY")+
  ylab("POLLUTION")

All days have a similar amount of pollution levels, however there is a day that stands out from the rest: day 302, which corresponds to October 28th with a pollution level of more than 2000 units

We want to see the day with the highest pollution value for the year 2022

max2022 <- which.max(poldia2$Polucion)
Oct30 <- max(poldia2$Polucion)

Contaminacio por horas

#CONTAMINACION POR HORAS
polhour <- group_by(air2, Hours)
polhour2 <- summarise(polhour, Polucion = mean(Pollution_lvl))
ggplot(polhour2)+
  geom_col(mapping = aes(x = Hours, y = Polucion))+
  labs(title = "POLLUTION LEVEL PER HOURS")+
  xlab("HOUR")+
  ylab("POLLUTION")

After analyzing the relationship between pollution levels and hours of the day, we observe that the values increase until 9 am, when it reaches a maximum point, and then decreases over the day until 4 pm, after that time, the pollution levels increase again reaching another maximum at 9 pm, then, the values decrease at night. The high pollution levels are probably due to the entering and exit hours of work/school and the low levels are due to the reduction of traffic.

CREATING A NEW DATASET WITH THE SIZE AND POPULATION IN EACH DISTRICT

We took the information from wikipedia and created the new dataset with vectors

#NUEVO DATASET CON LA DENSIDAD POR DISTRITO
DISTRICTE <- c("Ciutat Vella", "Eixample", "Sants-Montjuic", "Les Corts",
               "Sarria-Sant Gervasi", "Gracia", "Horta-Guinardo", "San Marti")
KM <- c(4.11, 7.46, 22.68, 6.02, 19.91, 4.19, 11.96, 10.39)
POBLACIO <- c(109672, 269349, 187026, 81576, 149201, 123276, 173944, 241181)

gente <- data.frame(DISTRICTE = DISTRICTE, KM2 = KM, POBLACIO = POBLACIO)

We do a left join with the dataset just created before and poltrees by the variable DISTRICT. Afterwards, we mutate the new dataset creating two new variables, DENSITAT and GREEN_LEVEL.

#RELACION ENTRE DENSIDAD Y POLUCION
polden <- left_join(poltrees, gente, by = "DISTRICTE")
polden2 <- mutate(polden, DENSITAT = POBLACIO/KM2)
polden2 <- mutate(polden2, GREEN_LEVEL = ARBRES/KM2)

Analyzing the Green level per each district

#GREEN LEVEL POR DISTRITO
glvl <- group_by(polden2, DISTRICTE)
slvl <- summarise(glvl, GREEN_LEVEL, KM2)
ggplot(slvl)+
  geom_col(mapping = aes(x = DISTRICTE, y = GREEN_LEVEL, fill = KM2))+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title = "GREEN LEVEL PER DISTRICT AND KM2")+
  xlab("GREEN LEVEL")+
  ylab("DISTRICT")

In this graph we see the relationship of the green level and the size of each district in km2. We can observe how San Martí is the greenest district and Sarrià-Sant Gervasi the least one. This graph is a clear relationship of what we were searching, the greener the area, the less polluted it is and the more polluted, the less density of trees there is.

Here we are evaluating the pollution levels of NO2 per district and the trees per km2. We can see that Eixample is the most polluted district but not the one that has the most km2 of trees. The least polluted one is Sarrià - Sant Gervasi and it’s the one that has less trees per km2. This means that there is no relationship between the amount of trees per km2 and the pollution levels of that district.

FINAL CONCLUSION

How are the pollution indexes evolving during the year? Is there any particular peak in any month, day or hour of the day that you consider concerning?

Looking at it from an overall perspective, if we take into account all the contaminants at the same time we see that there are both peaks in January and in July (at the beginning of every holiday). Then for every contaminant, the evolution during the months is slightly different. For the evolution of days of the year, if we take all contaminants, there is a very high peak on October 28th. Otherwise, for different contaminants, the peak is in another day. For the hours, as it was said, the hours of entry and exit from work are the most polluted.

Which is the impact of the “green level” (density of trees) in these indicators? Are the trees helping keep the air clean at all?

Yes, indeed there is a relationship between the green level (density of trees) and the pollution levels in general. That means, that the more polluted areas are the ones with the less density of trees and the more density of trees, the less pollution. On the contrary, if we look at it contaminant to contaminant, the relationship is not so obvious.

Which neighborhoods are more and which are less polluted? Which is the amount of population involved in the best (and worse) neighborhoods?

Horta Guinardó and Eixample are the neighborhoods with higher pollution level because they have the highest population density. Especially, in the case of Eixample, it is the more populated and the more polluted. Then, Horta-Guinardo is not so populated but it is contaminated. On the other hand, les Corts is the district with the lowest level of population and the lowest pollution level. Finally, the other neighborhoods like Sarria, Ciutat Vella, Gracia, Montjuic and Sant Marti, have different and high population density but have more or less the same pollution levels that compared to Horta and Eixample, they seem low.
